  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraping pipeline (SQLite + httpx), not a web app — there's no React/frontend code in the repo, so that category doesn't apply. I found a real N+1 pattern, a redundant-computation issue, and a high-leverage caching gap. No memory leaks (the process is short-lived per CLI invocation and everything is scoped to `run()`).\n\n### 1. N+1 query — `store.py:55-74` (the big one)\n\n`Store.diff()` issues one `SELECT` per job, in a Python loop, for every listing fetched this run:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nFor large boards (Amazon/Microsoft/Apple/Google can each return hundreds–thousands of listings per run, every 12h per the scheduled-run commit), that's hundreds–thousands of individual round trips through the sqlite3/Python boundary instead of one batched query.\n\n**Fix** — prefetch all existing hashes in one (or few, chunked) `IN (...)` query, then batch the writes with `executemany`:\n\n```python\n_CHUNK = 500  # stay under SQLite's default ~999 bound-parameter limit\n\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), _CHUNK):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + _CHUNK]\n        qmarks = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        for row in cur.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qmarks})\", chunk):\n            existing[row[\"key\"]] = row[\"content_hash\"]\n\n    new, changed, unchanged = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        (new if prev is None else changed if prev != job.content_hash else unchanged).append(job)\n\n    if new:\n        cur.executemany(_INSERT_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    if changed:\n        cur.executemany(_UPDATE_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    if unchanged:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                         [(now, j.key) for j in unchanged])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nTurns O(N) round trips into O(N/500) reads + 3 batched writes.\n\n### 2. Redundant per-job regex rebuilding — `filters.py:11-54`\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside the per-job call** — rebuilding the pattern list (re-escaping + re-`compile`-ing every keyword) for every single job:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n```\n\nCPython's `re` module caches parsed patterns internally, so this isn't a full re-parse each time, but it's still N × M wasted list allocations, `re.escape` calls, and cache lookups (N = jobs, M = keywords). Trivial to hoist out of the loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                       locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=(), exclude=(), locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n(`match` now takes pre-compiled `Pattern` lists instead of raw keyword strings.)\n\n### 3. Biggest caching opportunity — full board re-fetch every run (`fetchers.py`)\n\nEvery pagination loop (`fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_apple`, `fetch_eightfold`, `fetch_bytedance`, `fetch_phenom`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver`) only stops when a page returns *no IDs unseen within this run* (`fresh` empty). It has no idea what's already in the store, so on a 12h scheduled run it re-fetches the **entire board** — up to `max_pages` × page-size (e.g. Amazon: 40×10=400, Microsoft: 40×10=400, Google: 20×~20=400) — even though most of those postings are already known and only the first page or two are actually new.\n\nNearly every one of these sources is explicitly sorted newest-first (`sort=recent`, `sort_by=timestamp`, `sort: \"newest\"`, `sort_by_new: True`), which makes an early-stop cheap to add. Threading the store's known keys (or the last-scan watermark) into `fetch_all`/`fetch_source` and breaking once a full page is already-known would cut most of these runs from tens of pages to 1-2:\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_amazon(client, source, known_keys: frozenset[str] = frozenset()) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    for pg in range(max_pages):\n        data = await _get_json(...)\n        batch = parse_amazon(company, (data or {}).get(\"jobs\") or [])\n        fresh = [j for j in batch if j.external_id not in seen]\n        if not fresh:\n            break\n        seen.update(j.external_id for j in fresh)\n        jobs.extend(fresh)\n        if known_keys and all(j.key in known_keys for j in batch):  # newest-first: nothing older is new either\n            break\n    return jobs\n```\n\nThis is architecturally a bit bigger (pipeline.py would need to pass `store`-known keys into `fetch_all`), but it's the single highest-leverage change here — it turns O(board size) HTTP requests per run into O(new postings since last run).\n\n### 4. Minor / low-priority\n\n- `Job.content_hash` and `Job.key` (`models.py:55-69`) are plain `@property`s, recomputed on every access (`diff()` reads `job.content_hash` once, then `to_row()` recomputes it again for every new/changed job). Cheap (short-string SHA-256), not worth optimizing unless profiling shows it matters — `slots=True` on the dataclass also rules out a simple `functools.cached_property` without adding an explicit cache field.\n- Nothing else stood out as a leak: `Store` is always used via `with`, `httpx.AsyncClient` is closed in a `finally` in `fetch_all`, and each CLI invocation is a short-lived process.\n\n**Not applicable:** no React/frontend code exists in this repo (`agent.py` is a CLI launcher for Claude Code, not a UI).\n\nWant me to implement fixes #1 and #2 (both are safe, self-contained, easy to verify) — and/or sketch out the store-aware early-stop plumbing for #3?\n",
